High pressure is adiabatic compression when water vapor moves upward due to the influence of falling air currents.
The low pressure expands insulation under the influence of rising air currents.
Compression and expansion during adiabatic changes refer to the volume change of air.
When the surrounding pressure increases, compression occurs and the volume decreases, and when the surrounding pressure decreases, the volume increases and expands.

The pressure in the atmosphere also decreases as it goes up and increases as it goes down. This reduces the pressure (barometric pressure) because the distribution of the atmosphere is concentrated near the surface of the earth, so that the amount of atmosphere decreases as it goes up.

Then, the reason why it is insulation compression at high pressure and insulation expansion at low pressure is that downward airflow develops at high pressure and upward airflow develops at low pressure.

Then, at high pressure, the air is lowered because it is a descending airflow, and when the air is lowered, the ambient pressure (air pressure) increases, resulting in adiabatic compression. On the contrary, the low pressure is an ascending air current, so the air rises, and when the air rises, the surrounding pressure (air pressure) decreases, so it expands.
